  "prompt": "Can a Roman Catholic boy from Kerala marry a Hindu girl from another state?",
  "response": "Yes, a Roman Catholic boy from Kerala can marry a Hindu girl from another state. Interfaith marriages are legally permitted in India under the Special Marriage Act, 1954, which allows individuals of different religions to marry without needing to convert. The couple can register their marriage under this act, which recognizes the union and provides legal validity.\n\nHowever, interfaith marriages may also involve cultural and familial considerations. It is essential for the couple to discuss their expectations, beliefs, and values, and ensure mutual respect and understanding. They may also need to address any concerns or opposition from their families or communities. Communication, empathy, and support from both partners are crucial for navigating these personal and societal complexities.",
